by Western Fardelshufflestein » Tue Jun 22, 2021 5:26 pm

The Black Remnant wrote:
Nationalist Northumbria wrote:People having leaders that they try to make 'flawed'. My nation's leader, President Alvin Ashleigh, is not flawed, and I am proud of that.


Characters do not necessarily need to have flaws-this is true-but only if they can be written in a compelling way.
Considering your current writing repertoire mainly consists of one liner posts in an RP about northumbria seceding from britain, I'm going to make a big ol reach here and say that you don't fulfill those qualities.

Characters do, for the most part, need a flaw. It doesn't need to be something crippling, or something that drags them down, but an issue they have-they could be overly perfectionist, emotionally numb, just as much as they could be depressed or anxious or even more severe ones like afflicted with terminal cancer, blind/deaf, or just straight up paralyzed.

It's not something you tack on for brownie points, its something you ingrain as part of making a character more than a puppet to move around.

However, do not make that flaw the entirety of the character's personality. They should have personal qualities beyond said flaw--for instance, to reach for low-hanging fruit, Alastair is an end-stage alcoholic. I've made this a huge focus of his character as I've developed him, and I'm sure I fell prey to this last summer, but there is much more to his character than drincc. For instance, Alastair is (tries to be) a family man, and he cares deeply for his wife and children. He was very attached to his father before the elder died; Alastair III's death greatly impacted him in an extremely negative way. Alastair was known for his goofy sense of humor before he was injured, and he's been known for his altruism both before and after his extended hospital residency.

To get back on topic before I write another essay about Alastair, I'll explain what point I'm trying to illustrate. While Alastair's addiction has infiltrated every single aspect of his life being an addict isn't his only personality trait. He's an extremely complex man with a lifetime of struggles and internal demons (if I've done my job correctly). He isn't just a semi-vacant person being cared for in an addiction center.

This is slightly tangential, but for character flaws that fall under things like addiction and disability, make sure to do some research to make it as accurate as possible. Try to know what stereotypes to avoid and what stigmas surround people with that particular disability. It also helps to imagine things from that character's perspective (ie, in the first person). What is their daily life like? How do they feel about their disability, and how do they work with and/or around it? Speaking of which, a stereotype that I know is negative (I am obviously far from an expert on this, or course) is a disabled character being magically cured of whatever it is that's supposedly ailing them. People can live fulfilling lives regardless of whether they're blind/deaf/paralyzed--not to discount what they go through, of course, because I don't know and am not speaking from experience.

Also, try not to make that character's life center around said disability--don't make it the entirety of their arc. Their lives should be as nuanced and complicated as non-disabled characters'.
